04054nam a22007095i 9780814708873DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147088737 a10.18574/97808147088732doi  a(DE-B1597)548611  a(OCoLC)646824799  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF480 .S29 2009 7aHIS0540002bisacsh04a346.7301/31 aSchweik, Susan M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Ugly Laws :bDisability in Public /cSusan M. Schweik. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe History of Disability ;v300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. PRODUCING THE UNSIGHTLY -- t2. GETTING UGLY -- t3. THE LAW IN CONTEXT -- t4. THE LAW IN LANGUAGE -- t5. DISSIMULATIONS -- t6. GENDER, SEXUALITY, AND THE UGLY LAW -- t7. IMMIGRATION, ETHNICITY, AND THE UGLY LAW -- t8. RACE, SEGREGATION, AND THE UGLY LAW -- t9. THE RIGHT TO THE CITY -- t10. REHABILITATING THE UNSIGHTLY -- t11. ALL ABOUT UGLY LAWS (FOR TEN CENTS) -- tCONCLUSION -- tAPPENDIX -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the late-nineteenth and early-twentieth centuries, municipallaws targeting "unsightly beggars" sprang up in cities across America. Seeming to criminalize disability and thus offering a visceral example of discrimination, these "ugly laws" have become a sort of shorthand for oppression in disability studies, law, and the arts.In this watershed study of the ugly laws, Susan M. Schweik uncovers the murky history behind the laws, situating the varied legislation in its historical context and exploring in detail what the laws meant. Illustrating how the laws join the history of the disabled and the poor, Schweik not only gives the reader a deeper understanding of the ugly laws and the cities where they were generated, she locates the laws at a crucial intersection of evolving and unstable concepts of race, nation, sex, class, and gender. Moreover, she explores the history of resistance to the ordinances, using the often harrowing life stories of those most affected by their passage. Moving to the laws' more recent history, Schweik analyzes the shifting cultural memory of the ugly laws, examining how they have been used-and misused-by academics, activists, artists, lawyers, and legislators.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 4aAmericas. 4achapter. 4ahard. 4ahistory. 4alook. 4augly. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814708873423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814708873.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK